[AI] ----- institutional brief (plain text) -----
US?DE 10Y spread at 1.25 percent remains the dominant cross-asset signal while US?JP rates remain opaque and volatility regimes diverge sharply across G10.

EUR/USD sits in neutral territory with minimal model conviction at just five percent, anchored to the 1.25 percentage point US?DE spread widening marginally to cover US rate premium. Leveraged positioning has crept into the neutral long territory at the 55th percentile, and asset managers are crowded short at the fifth percentile, leaving the pair vulnerable to positioning unwind once volatility normalizes from its elevated 87th percentile reading. The regime correlation has weakened to 0.317 over 60 days, signaling the spread transmission mechanism is losing grip; elevated vol obscures whether to trust the mean reversion. Watch whether the asset manager short unwinds faster than the spread itself tightens, as that divergence would send EUR/USD lower despite rate support.

USD/JPY labors in unknown regime territory with fifty percent model confidence because US?JP 10Y data is missing and BoJ policy uncertainty clouds the cross. Leveraged money sits at the 34th percentile short, below neutral, while asset managers are heavily crowded into a short at just the third percentile?a classic setup for carry-trade deleveraging if risk appetite cracks. Realized volatility at just the 19th percentile sits well below USD/JPY's historical norm, masking latent positioning risk. The next catalyst to monitor is any BoJ communication signaling hawkishness or forward guidance on rate path, which would force covering shorts and spike vol.

USD/INR clings to neutral despite all-time high realized volatility at the 100th percentile, with RBI actively defending the currency through four point seven billion dollars of reserve drawdown over seven days. The US?IN spread has compressed 2.79 percentage points, turning into a headwind for rupee strength, while gold correlation has inverted to negative (minus 0.266) in what the desk flags as a Akshaya Tritiya seasonal effect, breaking the normal import-demand channel. FPI flow is still a net positive at plus 25 in the composite score, but RBI support is straining at minus six. Watch whether RBI reserves continue to drain; if drawdowns accelerate past current pace or cross psychological thresholds, INR support becomes structural and defensive rather than temporary.
